<p class="">    <h1>Key Challenges in the Small-Scale LNG Market</h1>    <ul>        <li>            <strong>Infrastructure Limitations:</strong>             <p>The small-scale LNG market suffers from inadequate infrastructure, particularly in regions lacking terminal facilities. The high capital costs associated with building liquefaction and regasification plants deter investment.</p>        </li>        <li>            <strong>Regulatory Hurdles:</strong>            <p>Complex regulatory frameworks create significant barriers to entry. Inconsistent policies across different jurisdictions hinder the development of a cohesive market.</p>        </li>        <li>            <strong>Market Volatility:</strong>            <p>The LNG market is subject to price fluctuations due to factors such as geopolitical tensions, changes in demand, and competition from alternative energy sources, affecting profitability.</p>        </li>        <li>            <strong>Limited Awareness and Adoption:</strong>            <p>Despite environmental benefits, awareness of small-scale LNG advantages compared to traditional fuels remains low, impeding adoption.</p>        </li>        <li>            <strong>Technical Challenges:</strong>            <p>Challenges in technology for liquefaction and transportation, including efficiency and emission control, require continuous innovation and investment.</p>        </li>    </ul>    <h2>Potential Growth Opportunities in the Small-Scale LNG Market</h1>    <ul>        <li>            <strong>Emerging Demand for Cleaner Fuels:</strong>             <p>As countries aim to meet climate goals, the demand for cleaner fuels is increasing. Small-scale LNG presents a viable alternative for industries looking to reduce their carbon footprint.</p>        </li>        <li>            <strong>Maritime Sector Use:</strong>            <p>The maritime sector is seeking to adopt LNG as a cleaner fuel to comply with International Maritime Organization (IMO) regu